# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: win32-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Data files with the same file format as a DLL, but with different file extensions and possibly containing only resource sections, can be called *resource DLLs*.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Examples of such DLLs include *icon libraries*, sometimes having the extension `ICL`, and font files, having the extensions `FON` and `FOT`.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The first versions of Microsoft Windows ran programs together in a single address space.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Every program was meant to co-operate by yielding the CPU to other programs so that the graphical user interface (GUI) could multitask and be maximally responsive.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] All operating-system level operations were provided by the underlying operating system: MS-DOS.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] All higher-level services were provided by Windows Libraries "Dynamic Link Library".
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The Drawing API, Graphics Device Interface (GDI), was implemented in a DLL called `GDI.EXE`, the user interface in `USER.EXE`.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] These extra layers on top of DOS had to be shared across all running Windows programs, not just to enable Windows to work in a machine with less than a megabyte of RAM, but to enable the programs to co-operate with each other.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The code in GDI needed to translate drawing commands to operations on specific devices.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] On the display, it had to manipulate pixels in the frame buffer.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] When drawing to a printer, the API calls had to be transformed into requests to a printer.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Although it could have been possible to provide hard-coded support for a limited set of devices (like the Color Graphics Adapter display, the HP LaserJet Printer Command Language), Microsoft chose a different approach.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] GDI would work by loading different pieces of code, called "device drivers", to work with different output devices.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The same architectural concept that allowed GDI to load different device drivers also allowed the Windows shell to load different Windows programs, and for these programs to invoke API calls from the shared USER and GDI libraries.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] In a conventional non-shared static library, sections of code are simply added to the calling program when its executable is built at the "linking" phase; if two programs call the same routine, the routine is included in both the programs during the linking stage of the two.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] With dynamic linking, shared code is placed into a single, separate file.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The programs that call this file are connected to it at run time, with the operating system (or, in the case of early versions of Windows, the OS-extension), performing the binding.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] For those early versions of Windows (1.0 to 3.11), the DLLs were the foundation for the entire GUI.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] This notion of building up the operating system from a collection of dynamically loaded libraries is a core concept of Windows that persists as of 2015.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] DLLs provide the standard benefits of shared libraries, such as modularity.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Modularity allows changes to be made to code and data in a single self-contained DLL shared by several applications without any change to the applications themselves.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Another benefit of modularity is the use of generic interfaces for plug-ins.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] A single interface may be developed which allows old as well as new modules to be integrated seamlessly at run-time into pre-existing applications, without any modification to the application itself.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] This concept of dynamic extensibility is taken to the extreme with the Component Object Model, the underpinnings of ActiveX.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] In Windows 1.x, 2.x and 3.x, all Windows applications shared the same address space as well as the same memory.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] A DLL was only loaded once into this address space; from then on, all programs using the library accessed it.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The library's data was shared across all the programs.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] This could be used as an indirect form of inter-process communication, or it could accidentally corrupt the different programs.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] With the introduction of 32-bit libraries in Windows 95, every process ran in its own address space.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] While the DLL code may be shared, the data is private except where shared data is explicitly requested by the library.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] That said, large swathes of Windows 95, Windows 98 and Windows Me were built from 16-bit libraries, which limited the performance of the Pentium Pro microprocessor when launched, and ultimately limited the stability and scalability of the DOS-based versions of Windows.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Although DLLs are the core of the Windows architecture, they have several drawbacks, collectively called "DLL hell".
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] As of 2015 Microsoft promotes .NET Framework as one solution to the problems of DLL hell, although they now promote virtualization-based solutions such as Microsoft Virtual PC and Microsoft Application Virtualization, because they offer superior isolation between applications.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] An alternative mitigating solution to DLL hell has been to implement side-by-side assembly.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Since DLLs are essentially the same as EXEs, the choice of which to produce as part of the linking process is for clarity, since it is possible to export functions and data from either.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] DLLs provide a mechanism for shared code and data, allowing a developer of shared code/data to upgrade functionality without requiring applications to be re-linked or re-compiled.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] From the application development point of view, Windows and OS/2 can be thought of as a collection of DLLs that are upgraded, allowing applications for one version of the OS to work in a later one, provided that the OS vendor has ensured that the interfaces and functionality are compatible.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] DLLs execute in the memory space of the calling process and with the same access permissions, which means there is little overhead in their use, but also that there is no protection for the calling program if the DLL has any sort of bug.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] In Windows API, DLL files are organized into *sections*.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Each section has its own set of attributes, such as being writable or read-only, executable (for code) or non-executable (for data), and so on.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The code in a DLL is usually shared among all the processes that use the DLL; that is, they occupy a single place in physical memory, and do not take up space in the page file.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Windows does not use position-independent code for its DLLs; instead, the code undergoes relocation as it is loaded, fixing addresses for all its entry points at locations which are free in the memory space of the first process to load the DLL.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] In older versions of Windows, in which all running processes occupied a single common address space, a single copy of the DLL's code would always be sufficient for all the processes.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] However, in newer versions of Windows which use separate address spaces for each program, it is only possible to use the same relocated copy of the DLL in multiple programs if each program has the same virtual addresses free to accommodate the DLL's code.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] If some programs (or their combination of already-loaded DLLs) do not have those addresses free, then an additional physical copy of the DLL's code will need to be created, using a different set of relocated entry points.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] If the physical memory occupied by a code section is to be reclaimed, its contents are discarded, and later reloaded directly from the DLL file as necessary.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] In contrast to code sections, the data sections of a DLL are usually private; that is, each process using the DLL has its own copy of all the DLL's data.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Optionally, data sections can be made shared, allowing inter-process communication via this shared memory area.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] However, because user restrictions do not apply to the use of shared DLL memory, this creates a security hole; namely, one process can corrupt the shared data, which will likely cause all other sharing processes to behave undesirably.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] For example, a process running under a guest account can in this way corrupt another process running under a privileged account.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] This is an important reason to avoid the use of shared sections in DLLs.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] If a DLL is compressed by certain executable packers (e.g.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] UPX), all of its code sections are marked as read and write, and will be unshared.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Read-and-write code sections, much like private data sections, are private to each process.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Thus DLLs with shared data sections should not be compressed if they are intended to be used simultaneously by multiple programs, since each program instance would have to carry its own copy of the DLL, resulting in increased memory consumption.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Like static libraries, import libraries for DLLs are noted by the `.lib` file extension.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] For example, kernel32.dll, the primary dynamic library for Windows's base functions such as file creation and memory management, is linked via `kernel32.lib`.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The usual way to tell an import library from a proper static library is by size: the import library is much smaller as it only contains symbols referring to the actual DLL, to be processed at link-time.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Both nevertheless are Unix ar format files.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Linking to dynamic libraries is usually handled by linking to an import library when building or linking to create an executable file.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The created executable then contains an import address table (IAT) by which all DLL function calls are referenced (each referenced DLL function contains its own entry in the IAT).
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] At run-time, the IAT is filled with appropriate addresses that point directly to a function in the separately loaded DLL.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] In Cygwin/MSYS and MinGW, import libraries are conventionally given the suffix `.dll.a`, combining both the Windows DLL suffix and the Unix ar suffix.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The file format is similar, but the symbols used to mark the imports are different (`_head_foo_dll` vs `__IMPORT_DESCRIPTOR_foo`).
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Although its GNU Binutils toolchain can generate import libraries and link to them, it is faster to link to the DLL directly.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] An experimental tool in MinGW called genlib can be used to generate import libs with MSVC-style symbols.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Each function exported by a DLL is identified by a numeric ordinal and optionally a name.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Likewise, functions can be imported from a DLL either by ordinal or by name.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The ordinal represents the position of the function's address pointer in the DLL Export Address table.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] It is common for internal functions to be exported by ordinal only.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] For most Windows API functions only the names are preserved across different Windows releases; the ordinals are subject to change.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Thus, one cannot reliably import Windows API functions by their ordinals.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Importing functions by ordinal provides only slightly better performance than importing them by name: export tables of DLLs are ordered by name, so a binary search can be used to find a function.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The index of the found name is then used to look up the ordinal in the Export Ordinal table.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] In 16-bit Windows, the name table was not sorted, so the name lookup overhead was much more noticeable.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] It is also possible to *bind* an executable to a specific version of a DLL, that is, to resolve the addresses of imported functions at compile-time.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] For bound imports, the linker saves the timestamp and checksum of the DLL to which the import is bound.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] At run-time, Windows checks to see if the same version of library is being used, and if so, Windows bypasses processing the imports.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Otherwise, if the library is different from the one which was bound to, Windows processes the imports in a normal way.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Bound executables load somewhat faster if they are run in the same environment that they were compiled for, and exactly the same time if they are run in a different environment, so there is no drawback for binding the imports.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] For example, all the standard Windows applications are bound to the system DLLs of their respective Windows release.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] A good opportunity to bind an application's imports to its target environment is during the application's installation.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] This keeps the libraries "bound" until the next OS update.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] It does, however, change the checksum of the executable, so it is not something that can be done with signed programs, or programs that are managed by a configuration management tool that uses checksums (such as MD5 checksums) to manage file versions.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] As more recent Windows versions have moved away from having fixed addresses for every loaded library (for security reasons), the opportunity and value of binding an executable is decreasing.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] DLL files may be explicitly loaded at run-time, a process referred to simply as *run-time dynamic linking* by Microsoft, by using the `LoadLibrary` (or `LoadLibraryEx`) API function.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The `GetProcAddress` API function is used to look up exported symbols by name, and `FreeLibrary` – to unload the DLL.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] These functions are analogous to `dlopen`, `dlsym`, and `dlclose` in the POSIX standard API.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The procedure for explicit run-time linking is the same in any language that supports pointers to functions, since it depends on the Windows API rather than language constructs.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Normally, an application that is linked against a DLL’s import library will fail to start if the DLL cannot be found, because Windows will not run the application unless it can find all of the DLLs that the application may need.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] However an application may be linked against an import library to allow delayed loading of the dynamic library.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] In this case, the operating system will not try to find or load the DLL when the application starts; instead, a stub is included in the application by the linker which will try to find and load the DLL through `LoadLibrary` and `GetProcAddress` when one of its functions is called.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] If the DLL cannot be found or loaded, or the called function does not exist, the application will generate an exception, which may be caught and handled appropriately.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] If the application does not handle the exception, it will be caught by the operating system, which will terminate the program with an error message.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The delayed loading mechanism also provides notification hooks, allowing the application to perform additional processing or error handling when the DLL is loaded and/or any DLL function is called.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] In a source file, the keyword `library` is used instead of `program`.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] At the end of the file, the functions to be exported are listed in `exports` clause.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Delphi does not need `LIB` files to import functions from DLLs; to link to a DLL, the `external` keyword is used in the function declaration to signal the DLL name, followed by `name` to name the symbol (if different) or `index` to identify the index.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] In Visual Basic (VB), only run-time linking is supported; but in addition to using `LoadLibrary` and `GetProcAddress` API functions, *declarations* of imported functions are allowed.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] When importing DLL functions through declarations, VB will generate a run-time error if the `DLL` file cannot be found.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The developer can catch the error and handle it appropriately.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] When creating DLLs in VB, the IDE will only allow creation of ActiveX DLLs, however methods have been created to allow the user to explicitly tell the linker to include a .DEF file which defines the ordinal position and name of each exported function.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] This allows the user to create a standard Windows DLL using Visual Basic (Version 6 or lower) which can be referenced through a "Declare" statement.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Microsoft Visual C++ (MSVC) provides several extensions to standard C++ which allow functions to be specified as imported or exported directly in the C++ code; these have been adopted by other Windows C and C++ compilers, including Windows versions of GCC.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] These extensions use the attribute `__declspec` before a function declaration.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Note that when C functions are accessed from C++, they must also be declared as `extern "C"` in C++ code, to inform the compiler that the C linkage should be used.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Besides specifying imported or exported functions using `__declspec` attributes, they may be listed in IMPORT or EXPORTS section of the `DEF` file used by the project.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The `DEF` file is processed by the linker, rather than the compiler, and thus it is not specific to C++.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] DLL compilation will produce both `DLL` and `LIB` files.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The `LIB` file (import library) is used to link against a DLL at compile-time; it is not necessary for run-time linking.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Unless the DLL is a Component Object Model (COM) server, the `DLL` file must be placed in one of the directories listed in the PATH environment variable, in the default system directory, or in the same directory as the program using it.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] COM server DLLs are registered using regsvr32.exe, which places the DLL's location and its globally unique ID (GUID) in the registry.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Programs can then use the DLL by looking up its GUID in the registry to find its location or create an instance of the COM object indirectly using its class identifier and interface identifier.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The following examples show how to use language-specific bindings to import symbols for linking against a DLL at compile-time.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] 'Example.lib' file must be included (assuming that Example.dll is generated) in the project before static linking.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The file 'Example.lib' is automatically generated by the compiler when compiling the DLL.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Not executing the above statement would cause linking error as the linker would not know where to find the definition of `AddNumbers`.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The following examples show how to use the run-time loading and linking facilities using language-specific Windows API bindings.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Note that all of the four samples are vulnerable to DLL preloading attacks, since example.dll can be resolved to a place unintended by the author (the current working directory goes *before* system library locations), and thus to a malicious version of the library.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] See the reference for Microsoft's guidance on safe library loading: one should use `SetDllDirectoryW` in `kernel32` to remove the current-directory lookup before any libraries are loaded.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The Python ctypes binding will use POSIX API on POSIX systems.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The Component Object Model (COM) defines a binary standard to host the implementation of objects in DLL and EXE files.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] It provides mechanisms to locate and version those files as well as a language-independent and machine-readable description of the interface.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Hosting COM objects in a DLL is more lightweight and allows them to share resources with the client process.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] This allows COM objects to implement powerful back-ends to simple GUI front ends such as Visual Basic and ASP.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] They can also be programmed from scripting languages.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Due to a vulnerability commonly known as DLL hijacking, DLL spoofing, DLL preloading or binary planting, many programs will load and execute a malicious DLL contained in the same folder as a data file opened by these programs.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] The vulnerability was discovered by Georgi Guninski in 2000.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] In August 2010 it gained worldwide publicity after ACROS Security rediscovered it again and many hundreds of programs were found vulnerable.
[src:win32-api/dynamic-link-library] Programs that are run from unsafe locations, i.e. user-writable folders like the *Downloads* or the *Temp* directory, are almost always susceptible to this vulnerability.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] In computer programming, a **handle** is an abstract reference to a resource that is used when application software references blocks of memory or objects that are managed by another system like a database or an operating system.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] A resource handle can be an opaque identifier, in which case it is often an integer number (often an array index in an array or "table" that is used to manage that type of resource), or it can be a pointer that allows access to further information.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] Common resource handles include file descriptors, network sockets, database connections, process identifiers (PIDs), and job IDs.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] PIDs and job IDs are explicitly visible integers; while file descriptors and sockets (which are often implemented as a form of file descriptor) are represented as integers, they are typically considered opaque.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] In traditional implementations, file descriptors are indices into a (per-process) file descriptor table, thence a (system-wide) file table.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] Similarly, the extra layer of indirection also increases the control that the managing system has over the operations performed on the referent.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] Typically the handle is an index or a pointer into a global array of tombstones.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] A handle leak is a type of software bug that occurs when a computer program does not free a handle that it previously allocated.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] This is a form of resource leak, analogous to a memory leak for previously allocated memory.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] In secure computing terms, because access to a resource via a handle is mediated by another system, a handle functions as a *capability*: it not only identifies an object, but also associates access rights.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] For example, while a filename is forgeable (it is just a guessable identifier), a handle is *given* to a user by an external system, and thus represents not just identity, but also *granted* access.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] This call asks the operating system to open the specified file with the specified access rights.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] If the OS allows this, then it opens the file (creates an entry in the per-process file descriptor table) and returns a handle (file descriptor, index into this table) to the user: the actual access is controlled by the OS, and the handle is a token of that.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] Conversely, the OS may deny access, and thus neither open the file nor return a handle.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] In a capability-based system, handles can be passed between processes, with associated access rights.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] Note that in these cases the handle must be something other than a systemwide-unique small integer, otherwise it is forgeable.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] Such an integer may nevertheless be used to identify a capability inside a process; e.g., file descriptor in Linux is unforgeable because its numerical value alone is meaningless, and only in the process context may refer to anything.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] Transferring such a handle requires special care though, as its value often has to be different in the sending and receiving processes.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] In non-capability-based systems, on the other hand, each process must acquire its own separate handle, by specifying the identity of the resource and the desired access rights (e.g., each process must open a file itself, by giving the filename and access mode).
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] Such usage is more common even in modern systems that do support passing handles, but it is subject to vulnerabilities like the confused deputy problem.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] Handles were a popular solution to memory management in operating systems of the 1990s, such as Mac OS and Windows.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] The FILE data structure in the C standard I/O library is a file handle, abstracting from the underlying file representation (on Unix these are file descriptors).
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] Like other desktop environments, the Windows API heavily uses handles to represent objects in the system and to provide a communication pathway between the operating system and user space.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] For example, a window on the desktop is represented by a handle of type `HWND` (handle, window).
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] Doubly indirect handles (where the handle is not necessarily a pointer but might be, for example, an integer) have fallen out of favor in recent times, as increases in available memory and improved virtual memory algorithms have made the use of the simpler pointer more attractive.
[src:win32-api/handle-computing] However, many operating systems still apply the term to pointers to opaque, "private" data structures—opaque pointers—or to indexes into internal arrays passed from one process to its client.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] MFC was introduced by Microsoft in 1992 and quickly gained widespread use.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] While Microsoft has introduced alternative application frameworks since then, MFC remains widely used.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] MFC was introduced in 1992 with Microsoft's *C/C++ 7.0* compiler for use with 16-bit versions of Windows as an extremely thin object-oriented C++ wrapper for the Windows API.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] C++ was just beginning to replace C for development of commercial application software at the time.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] Direct Windows API calls in an MFC program are rarely needed.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] Instead programs create objects from Microsoft Foundation Class classes and call member functions belonging to those objects.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] Many of those functions share their names with corresponding API functions.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] One quirk of MFC is the use of "Afx" as the prefix for many functions, macros and the standard precompiled header name "stdafx.h".
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] During early development, what became MFC was called "Application Framework Extensions" and abbreviated "Afx".
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] The name Microsoft Foundation Classes (MFC) was adopted too late in the release cycle to change these references.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] MFC 8.0 was released with Visual Studio 2005.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] MFC 9.0 was released with Visual Studio 2008.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] On April 7, 2008, Microsoft released an update to the MFC classes as an out-of-band update to Visual Studio 2008 and MFC 9.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] The update features new user interface constructs, including the ribbons and associated UI widgets, fully customizable toolbars, docking panes which can either be freely floated or docked to any side and document tabs.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] MFC was initially a feature of the commercial versions of Visual Studio.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] As such, it is not included in the freeware Visual C++ Express.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] The Community edition of Visual Studio, introduced in 2014, however, includes MFC.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] Object Windows Library (OWL), designed for use with Borland's Turbo C++ compiler, was a competing product introduced by Borland around the same time.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] Eventually, Borland discontinued OWL development and licensed the distribution of the MFC headers, libraries and DLLs from Microsoft for a short time, though it never offered fully integrated support for MFC.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] Borland later released Visual Component Library to replace the OWL framework.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] MFC is a library that wraps portions of the Windows API in C++ classes, including functionality that enables them to use a default application framework.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] Classes are defined for many of the handle-managed Windows objects and also for predefined windows and common controls.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] At the time of its introduction, MFC provided C++ macros for Windows message-handling (via Message Maps), exceptions, run-time type information (RTTI), serialization and dynamic class instantiation.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] The macros for message-handling aimed to reduce memory consumption by avoiding gratuitous virtual table use and also to provide a more concrete structure for various Visual C++-supplied tools to edit and manipulate code without parsing the full language.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] The message-handling macros replaced the virtual function mechanism provided by C++.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] The macros for serialization, exceptions, and RTTI predated availability of these features in Microsoft C++ by a number of years.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] 32-bit versions of MFC, for Windows NT 3.1 and later Windows operating systems, used compilers that implemented the language features and updated the macros to simply wrap the language features instead of providing customized implementations, realizing upward compatibility.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] The MFC ribbon resource editor allows the developer to design the ribbon graphically instead of having to use the XML-based declarative markup like the RibbonX API.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] Optionally, ribbon components may be programmed directly by calling a new set of ribbon class methods.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] The developer may mix graphical and programmatic ribbon development as is convenient.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] The MFC application wizard has also been upgraded to support the new features, including a check-box to select whether the application will use the ribbon or the docking panes.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] The new functionality is provided in new classes so that old applications still continue to run.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] This update builds on top of BCGSoft’s BCGControlBar Library Professional Edition.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] Microsoft has imposed additional licensing requirements on users of the ribbons.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] These include a requirement to adhere to Microsoft UI Design Guidelines, and an anti-competition clause prohibiting the use of the UI in applications which compete with Microsoft Office.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-foundation-class-library] MFC can be used by linking a static library or by adding the MFC dynamic-link library (DLL).
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The first version of Windows, Windows 1.0, was released on November 20, 1985 as a graphical operating system shell for MS-DOS in response to growing interest in graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The name *Windows* is a reference to the windowing system in GUIs.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The 1990 release of Windows 3.0 catapulted its market success and led to the launch of various other product families, including the (now-defunct) Windows Mobile, Windows Phone, and Windows CE/Embedded Compact.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows is the most popular desktop operating system in the world, with a 77% market share as of May 2026, and the second-most popular operating system overall, behind Android.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] As of May 2026, Windows 11 is the most used desktop version of Windows, with a market share of 72%.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] All members of the Windows product family are, as of 2026, based on Windows NT.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The first version of Windows in that product line, Windows NT 3.1, was intended for server computing and corporate workstations.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] It now consists of four sub-families that tend to be released almost simultaneously and share the same kernel.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The term *Windows* collectively describes any or all of several generations of Microsoft operating system products.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The history of Windows dates back to 1981 when Microsoft started work on a program called "Interface Manager".
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The name "Windows" comes from the fact that the system was one of the first to use graphical boxes to represent programs; in the industry, at the time, these were called "windows" and the underlying software was called "windowing software".
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] It was announced in November 1983 (after the Apple Lisa, but before the Macintosh) under the name "Windows", but Windows 1.0 was not released until November 1985.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 1.0 was to compete with Apple's operating system, but achieved little popularity.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 1.0 is not a complete operating system; rather, it extends MS-DOS.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The shell of Windows 1.0 is a program known as the MS-DOS Executive.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Components included Calculator, Calendar, Cardfile, Clipboard Viewer, Clock, Control Panel, Notepad, Paint, Reversi, Terminal and Write.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 1.0 does not allow overlapping windows.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Only modal dialog boxes may appear over other windows.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Microsoft sold as included Windows Development libraries with the C development environment, which included numerous windows samples.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 2.0 was released in December 1987, and was more popular than its predecessor.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] It features several improvements to the user interface and memory management.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 2.03 changed the OS from tiled windows to overlapping windows.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The result of this change led to Apple Computer filing a suit against Microsoft alleging infringement on Apple's copyrights (eventually settled in court in Microsoft's favor in 1993).
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 2.0 also introduced more sophisticated keyboard shortcuts and could make use of expanded memory.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 2.1 was released in two different versions: Windows/286 and Windows/386.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows/386 uses the virtual 8086 mode of the Intel 80386 to multitask several DOS programs and the paged memory model to emulate expanded memory using available extended memory.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows/286, in spite of its name, runs on both Intel 8086 and Intel 80286 processors.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] It runs in real mode but can make use of the high memory area.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In addition to full Windows packages, there were runtime-only versions that shipped with early Windows software from third parties and made it possible to run their Windows software on MS-DOS and without the full Windows feature set.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The early versions of Windows are often thought of as graphical shells, mostly because they ran on top of MS-DOS and used it for file system services.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] However, even the earliest Windows versions already assumed many typical operating system functions; notably, having their own executable file format and providing their own device drivers (timer, graphics, printer, mouse, keyboard and sound).
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Unlike MS-DOS, Windows allowed users to execute multiple graphical applications at the same time, through cooperative multitasking.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.0, released in 1990, improved the design, mostly because of virtual memory and loadable virtual device drivers (VxDs) that allow Windows to share arbitrary devices between multi-tasked DOS applications.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.0 applications can run in protected mode, which gives them access to several megabytes of memory without the obligation to participate in the software virtual memory scheme.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] They run inside the same address space, where the segmented memory provides a degree of protection.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.0 also featured improvements to the user interface.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Microsoft rewrote critical operations from C into assembly.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.0 was the first version of Windows to achieve broad commercial success, selling 2 million copies in the first six months.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.1, made generally available on March 1, 1992, featured a facelift.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In October 1992, Windows for Workgroups, a special version with integrated peer-to-peer networking features, was released.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Support for Windows 3.1 ended on December 31, 2001.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.2, released in 1994, is an updated version of the Chinese version of Windows 3.1.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The update was limited to this language version, as it fixed only issues related to the complex writing system of the Chinese language.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.2 was generally sold by computer manufacturers with a ten-disk version of MS-DOS that also had Simplified Chinese characters in basic output and some translated utilities.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The next major consumer-oriented release of Windows, Windows 95, was released on August 24, 1995.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] While still remaining MS-DOS-based, Windows 95 introduced support for native 32-bit applications, plug and play hardware, preemptive multitasking, long file names of up to 255 characters, and provided increased stability over its predecessors.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 95 also introduced a redesigned, object oriented user interface, replacing the previous Program Manager with the Start menu, taskbar, and Windows Explorer shell.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The first OSR of Windows 95 was also the first version of Windows to be bundled with Microsoft's web browser, Internet Explorer.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Mainstream support for Windows 95 ended on December 31, 2000, and extended support for Windows 95 ended on December 31, 2001.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 95 was followed up with the release of Windows 98 on June 25, 1998, which introduced the Windows Driver Model, support for USB composite devices, support for ACPI, hibernation, and support for multi-monitor configurations.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 98 also included integration with Internet Explorer 4 through Active Desktop and other aspects of the Windows Desktop Update (a series of enhancements to the Explorer shell which was also made available for Windows 95).
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In June 1999, Microsoft released Windows 98 Second Edition, an updated version of Windows 98.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 98 SE added Internet Explorer 5.0 and Windows Media Player 6.2 amongst other upgrades.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Mainstream support for Windows 98 ended on June 30, 2002, and extended support for Windows 98 ended on July 11, 2006.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] On September 14, 2000, Microsoft released Windows Me (Millennium Edition), the last DOS-based version of Windows.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] However, Windows Me was faced with criticism for its speed and instability, along with hardware compatibility issues and its removal of real mode DOS support.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] *PC World* considered Windows Me to be one of the worst operating systems Microsoft had ever released, and the fourth worst tech product of all time.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In November 1988, a new development team within Microsoft (which included former Digital Equipment Corporation developers Dave Cutler and Mark Lucovsky) began work on a revamped version of IBM and Microsoft's OS/2 operating system known as "NT OS/2".
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] NT OS/2 was intended to be a secure, multi-user operating system with POSIX compatibility and a modular, portable kernel with preemptive multitasking and support for multiple processor architectures.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] However, following the successful release of Windows 3.0, the NT development team decided to rework the project to use an extended 32-bit port of the Windows API known as Win32 instead of those of OS/2.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Win32 maintained a similar structure to the Windows APIs (allowing existing Windows applications to easily be ported to the platform), but also supported the capabilities of the existing NT kernel.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Following its approval by Microsoft's staff, development continued on what was now Windows NT, the first 32-bit version of Windows.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] However, IBM objected to the changes, and ultimately continued OS/2 development on its own.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows NT was the first Windows operating system based on a hybrid kernel.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The hybrid kernel was designed as a modified microkernel, influenced by the Mach microkernel developed by Richard Rashid at Carnegie Mellon University, but without meeting all of the criteria of a pure microkernel.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The first release of the resulting operating system, Windows NT 3.1 (named to associate it with Windows 3.1) was released in July 1993, with versions for desktop workstations and servers.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows NT 3.5 was released in September 1994, focusing on performance improvements and support for Novell's NetWare, and was followed up by Windows NT 3.51 in May 1995, which included additional improvements and support for the PowerPC architecture.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows NT 4.0 was released in June 1996, introducing the redesigned interface of Windows 95 to the NT series.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] On February 17, 2000, Microsoft released Windows 2000, a successor to NT 4.0.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The Windows NT name was dropped at this point in order to put a greater focus on the Windows brand.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The next major version of Windows NT, Windows XP, was released to manufacturing (RTM) on August 24, 2001, and to the general public on October 25, 2001.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The introduction of Windows XP aimed to unify the consumer-oriented Windows 9x series with the architecture introduced by Windows NT, a change which Microsoft promised would provide better performance over its DOS-based predecessors.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] At retail, Windows XP was marketed in two main editions: the "Home" edition was targeted towards consumers, while the "Professional" edition was targeted towards business environments and power users, and included additional security and networking features.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Mainstream support for Windows XP ended on April 14, 2009.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Extended support ended on April 8, 2014.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] After Windows 2000, Microsoft also changed its release schedules for server operating systems; the server counterpart of Windows XP, Windows Server 2003, was released in April 2003.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] It was followed in March 2006, by Windows Server 2003 R2.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] After a lengthy development process, Windows Vista was released only for volume licensing on November 30, 2006, and finally, on January 30, 2007, it was officially released to everyone, including consumers.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] It contained a number of new features, from a redesigned shell and user interface to significant technical changes, with a particular focus on security features.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] It was available in a number of different editions, and has been subject to some criticism, such as drop of performance, longer boot time, criticism of new UAC, and stricter license agreement.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Vista's server counterpart, Windows Server 2008 was released in early 2008.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] On July 22, 2009, Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2 were released to manufacturing (RTM) and were officially released, including for the public, months later on October 22, 2009.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Unlike its predecessor, Windows Vista, which introduced a large number of new features, Windows 7 was intended to be a more focused, incremental upgrade to the Windows line, with the goal of being compatible with applications and hardware with which Windows Vista was already compatible.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 8, the successor to Windows 7, was released generally on October 26, 2012.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] A number of significant changes were made on Windows 8, including the introduction of a user interface based around Microsoft's Metro design language with optimizations for touch-based devices such as tablets and all-in-one PCs.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] These changes include the Start screen, which uses large tiles that are more convenient for touch interactions and allow for the display of continually updated information, and a new class of apps which are designed primarily for use on touch-based devices.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The new Windows version required a minimum resolution of 1024×768 pixels, effectively making it unfit for netbooks with 800×600-pixel screens.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] An update to Windows 8, called Windows 8.1, was released on October 17, 2013, and includes features such as new live tile sizes, deeper OneDrive integration, and many other revisions.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 8 and Windows 8.1 have been subject to some criticism, such as the removal of the Start menu.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] On September 30, 2014, Microsoft announced Windows 10 as the successor to Windows 8.1.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] It was released on July 29, 2015, and addresses shortcomings in the user interface first introduced with Windows 8.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Changes on PC include the return of the Start Menu, a virtual desktop system, and the ability to run Windows Store apps within windows on the desktop rather than in full-screen mode.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 10 is said to be available to update from qualified Windows 7 with SP1, Windows 8.1 and Windows Phone 8.1 devices from the Get Windows 10 Application (for Windows 7, Windows 8.1) or Windows Update (Windows 7).
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In February 2017, Microsoft announced the migration of its Windows source code repository from Perforce to Git.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] This migration involved 3.5 million separate files in a 300-gigabyte repository.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] By May 2017, 90 percent of its engineering team was using Git, in about 8500 commits and 1760 Windows builds per day.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In June 2021, shortly before Microsoft's announcement of Windows 11, Microsoft updated their lifecycle policy pages for Windows 10, revealing that support for their last release of Windows 10 will end on October 14, 2025.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] On April 27, 2023, Microsoft announced that version 22H2 would be the last of Windows 10.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] On June 24, 2021, Windows 11 was announced as the successor to Windows 10 during a livestream.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The new operating system was designed to be more user-friendly and understandable.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] As of May 2022, Windows 11 is a free upgrade to Windows 10 users who meet the system requirements.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In July 2021, Microsoft announced it will start selling subscriptions to virtualized Windows desktops as part of a new *Windows 365* service in the following month.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The new service will allow for cross-platform usage, aiming to make the operating system available for both Apple and Android users.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] It is a separate service and offers several variations including Windows 365 Frontline, Windows 365 Boot, and the Windows 365 app.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The subscription service will be accessible through any operating system with a web browser.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The new service is an attempt at capitalizing on the growing trend, fostered during the COVID-19 pandemic, for businesses to adopt a hybrid remote work environment, in which "employees split their time between the office and home".
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] As the service will be accessible through web browsers, Microsoft will be able to bypass the need to publish the service through Google Play or the Apple App Store.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Microsoft announced Windows 365 availability to business and enterprise customers on August 2, 2021.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Multilingual support has been built into Windows since Windows 3.0.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The language for both the keyboard and the interface can be changed through the Region and Language Control Panel.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Third-party IMEs may also be installed if a user feels that the provided one is insufficient for their needs.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Since Windows 2000, English editions of Windows NT have East Asian IMEs (such as Microsoft Pinyin IME and Microsoft Japanese IME) bundled, but files for East Asian languages may be manually installed on Control Panel.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Interface languages for the operating system are free for download, but some languages are limited to certain editions of Windows.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] This is used for most languages in emerging markets.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Full Language Packs, which translate the complete operating system, are only available for specific editions of Windows (Ultimate and Enterprise editions of Windows Vista and 7, and all editions of Windows 8, 8.1 and RT except Single Language).
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] They do not require a specific base language and are commonly used for more popular languages such as French or Chinese.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] These languages cannot be downloaded through the Download Center, but are available as optional updates through the Windows Update service (except Windows 8).
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The interface language of installed applications is not affected by changes in the Windows interface language.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The availability of languages depends on the application developers themselves.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 8 and Windows Server 2012 introduce a new Language Control Panel where both the interface and input languages can be simultaneously changed, and language packs, regardless of type, can be downloaded from a central location.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The PC Settings app in Windows 8.1 and Windows Server 2012 R2 also includes a counterpart settings page for this.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Changing the interface language also changes the language of preinstalled Windows Store apps (such as Mail, Maps and News) and certain other Microsoft-developed apps (such as Remote Desktop).
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The above limitations for language packs are however still in effect, except that full language packs can be installed for any edition except Single Language, which caters to emerging markets.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows NT included support for several platforms before the x86-based personal computer became dominant in the professional world.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows NT 4.0 and its predecessors supported PowerPC, DEC Alpha and MIPS R4000 (although some of the platforms implement 64-bit computing, the OS treated them as 32-bit).
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows 2000 dropped support for all platforms, except the third generation x86 (known as IA-32) or newer in 32-bit mode.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The client line of the Windows NT family still ran on IA-32 up to Windows 10 (the server line of the Windows NT family still ran on IA-32 up to Windows Server 2008).
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] With the introduction of the Intel Itanium architecture (IA-64), Microsoft released new versions of Windows to support it.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Itanium versions of Windows XP and Windows Server 2003 were released at the same time as their mainstream x86 counterparts.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows XP 64-Bit Edition (Version 2003), released in 2003, is the last Windows client operating system to support Itanium.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows Server line continues to support this platform until Windows Server 2012; Windows Server 2008 R2 is the last Windows operating system to support Itanium architecture.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] On April 25, 2005, Microsoft released Windows XP Professional x64 Edition and Windows Server 2003 x64 editions to support x86-64 (or simply x64), the 64-bit version of x86 architecture.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows Vista was the first client version of Windows NT to be released simultaneously in IA-32 and x64 editions.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] An edition of Windows 8 known as Windows RT was specifically created for computers with ARM architecture, and while ARM is still used for Windows smartphones with Windows 10, tablets with Windows RT will not be updated.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Starting from Windows 10 Fall Creators Update (version 1709) and later includes support for ARM-based PCs.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows CE (officially known as *Windows Embedded Compact*), is an edition of Windows that runs on minimalistic computers, like satellite navigation systems and some mobile phones.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows Embedded Compact is based on its own dedicated kernel, dubbed Windows CE kernel.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Microsoft licenses Windows CE to OEMs and device makers.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The OEMs and device makers can modify and create their own user interfaces and experiences, while Windows CE provides the technical foundation to do so.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows CE was used in the Dreamcast along with Sega's own proprietary OS for the console.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows CE was the core from which Windows Mobile was derived.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Its successor, Windows Phone 7, was based on components from both Windows CE 6.0 R3 and Windows CE 7.0.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows Phone 8 however, is based on the same NT-kernel as Windows 8.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows Embedded Compact is not to be confused with Windows XP Embedded or Windows NT 4.0 Embedded, modular editions of Windows based on Windows NT kernel.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Xbox OS is an unofficial name given to the version of Windows that runs on Xbox consoles.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] From Xbox One onwards it is an implementation with an emphasis on virtualization (using Hyper-V) as it is three operating systems running at once, consisting of the core operating system, a second implemented for games and a more Windows-like environment for applications.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Microsoft updates Xbox One's OS every month, and these updates can be downloaded from the Xbox Live service to the Xbox and subsequently installed, or by using offline recovery images downloaded via a PC.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] It was originally based on NT 6.2 (Windows 8) kernel, and the latest version runs on an NT 10.0 base.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] This system is sometimes referred to as "Windows 10 on Xbox One".
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Xbox One and Xbox Series operating systems also allow limited (due to licensing restrictions and testing resources) backward compatibility with previous generation hardware, and the Xbox 360's system is backwards compatible with the original Xbox.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Up to and including every version before Windows 2000, Microsoft used an in-house version control system named Source Library Manager (SLM).
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Shortly after Windows 2000 was released, Microsoft switched to a fork of Perforce named Source Depot.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] This system was used up until 2017 when the system could not keep up with the size of Windows.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Microsoft had begun to integrate Git into Team Foundation Server in 2013, but Windows (and Office) continued to rely on Source Depot.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The Windows code in Source Depot was divided among 65 different repositories.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In 2017 Microsoft announced that it would start using Git, an open source version control system created by Linus Torvalds, and in May 2017 they reported that the migration into a new Git repository was complete.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Each Git repository contains a complete history of all the files, which tends to be very large for Windows.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Microsoft has been working on a new project called the Virtual File System for Git (VFSForGit) to address these challenges.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In 2021 the VFS for Git was superseded by **Scalar**.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Use of Windows 10 has exceeded Windows 7 globally since early 2018.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Those statistics do not include servers (including cloud computing, where Linux has significantly more market share than Windows) as Net Applications and StatCounter use web browsing as a proxy for all use.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] While the Windows 9x series offered the option of having profiles for multiple users with separate profiles and home folders, it had no concept of access privileges, allowing any user to edit others' files.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In addition, while it ran separate 32-bit applications in separate address spaces, protecting an application's code and data from being read or written by another application, it did not protect the first megabyte of memory from userland applications for compatibility reasons.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] This area of memory contains code critical to the functioning of the operating system, and by writing into this area of memory an application can crash or freeze the operating system.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] This was a source of instability as faulty applications could accidentally write into this region, potentially corrupting important operating system memory, which usually resulted in some form of system error and halt.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows NT was far more secure, implementing access privileges and full memory protection, and, while 32-bit programs meeting the DoD's C2 security rating.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Prior to Windows Vista, the default user account created during the setup process was an administrator account; the user, and any program the user launched, had full access to the machine.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Though Windows XP did offer an option of turning administrator accounts into limited accounts, the majority of home users did not do so, partially due to the number of programs which required administrator rights to function properly.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] As a result, most home users still ran as administrator all the time.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] These architectural flaws, combined with Windows's very high popularity, made Windows a frequent target of computer worm and virus writers.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Furthermore, although Windows NT and its successors are designed for security (including on a network) and multi-user PCs, they were not initially designed with Internet security in mind as much, since, when it was first developed in the early 1990s, Internet use was less prevalent.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In a 2002 strategy memo entitled "Trustworthy computing" sent to every Microsoft employee, Bill Gates declared that security should become Microsoft's highest priority.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows Vista introduced a privilege elevation system called User Account Control.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] When logging in as a standard user, a logon session is created and a token containing only the most basic privileges is assigned.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In this way, the new logon session is incapable of making changes that would affect the entire system.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] When logging in as a user in the Administrators group, two separate tokens are assigned.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] The first token contains all privileges typically awarded to an administrator, and the second is a restricted token similar to what a standard user would receive.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] User applications, including the Windows shell, are then started with the restricted token, resulting in a reduced privilege environment even under an Administrator account.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Leaked documents from 2013 to 2016 codenamed Vault 7 detail the capabilities of the CIA to perform electronic surveillance and cyber warfare, such as the ability to compromise operating systems such as Windows.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In addition, experts reported a Microsoft security vulnerability, CVE-2019-1162, based on legacy code involving Microsoft CTF and ctfmon (ctfmon.exe), that affects all Windows versions from Windows XP to the then most recent Windows 10 versions; a patch to correct the flaw is available.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Microsoft releases security patches through its Windows Update service approximately once a month (usually the second Tuesday of the month), although critical updates are made available at shorter intervals when necessary.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Versions subsequent to Windows 2000 SP3 and Windows XP implemented automatic download and installation of updates, substantially increasing the number of users installing security updates.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows integrates the Windows Defender antivirus, which is seen as one of the best available.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Windows also implements Secure Boot, Control Flow Guard, ransomware protection, BitLocker disk encryption, a firewall, and Windows SmartScreen.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In July 2024, Microsoft signalled an intention to limit kernel access and improve overall security, following a highly publicised CrowdStrike update that caused 8.5 million Windows PCs to crash.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Part of that initiative is to rewrite parts of Windows in Rust, a memory-safe language.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] In 2025 Microsoft stopped offering support to Window 10 users, including providing security updates.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Microsoft encouraged people to upgrade to Windows 11 or if this wasn't possible, to sign-up for extended security updates.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] All Windows versions from Windows NT 3 have been based on a file system permission system referred to as AGDLP (Accounts, Global, Domain Local, Permissions) in which file permissions are applied to the file/folder in the form of a 'local group' which then has other 'global groups' as members.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] These global groups then hold other groups or users depending on different Windows versions used.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] This system varies from other vendor products such as Linux and NetWare due to the 'static' allocation of permission being applied directly to the file or folder.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] However using this process of AGLP/AGDLP/AGUDLP allows a small number of static permissions to be applied and allows for easy changes to the account groups without reapplying the file permissions on the files and folders.
[src:win32-api/microsoft-windows] Owing to the operating system's popularity, a number of applications have been released that aim to provide compatibility with Windows applications, either as a compatibility layer for another operating system, or as a standalone system that can run software written for Windows out of the box.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The **Windows API**, informally **WinAPI**, is the foundational application programming interface (API) that allows a computer program to access the features of the Microsoft Windows operating system in which the program is running.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Programs typically access this API using system libraries, which are shared libraries.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Each major version of the Windows API has a distinct name that identifies a compatibility aspect of that version.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] For example, Win32 is the major version of Windows API that runs on 32-bit systems.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The name, Windows API, collectively refers to all versions of this capability of Windows.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Microsoft provides developer support via a software development kit, Microsoft Windows SDK, which includes documentation and tools for building software based on the Windows API.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] This section lists notable services provided by the Windows API.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Base services include features such as the file system, devices, processes, threads, and error handling.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] These functions reside in kernel.exe, krnl286.exe or krnl386.exe files on 16-bit Windows, and kernel32.dll and KernelBase.dll on 32 and 64 bit Windows.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] These files reside in the folder \Windows\System32 on all versions of Windows.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Advanced services include features beyond the kernel like the Windows registry, shutdown/restart the system (or abort), start/stop/create a Windows service, manage user accounts.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] These functions reside in advapi32.dll and advapires32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The Graphics Device Interface (GDI) component provides features to output graphics content to monitors, printers, and other output devices.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] It resides in gdi.exe on 16-bit Windows, and gdi32.dll on 32-bit Windows in user-mode.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Kernel-mode GDI support is provided by `win32k.sys` which communicates directly with the graphics driver.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The User Interface component provides features to create and manage screen windows and most basic controls, such as buttons and scrollbars, receive mouse and keyboard input, and other functions associated with the graphical user interface (GUI) part of Windows.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] This functional unit resides in user.exe on 16-bit Windows, and user32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Since Windows XP versions, the basic controls reside in comctl32.dll, together with the common controls (Common Control Library).
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The Common Dialog Box Library provides standard dialog boxes to open and save files, choose color and font, etc.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The library resides in a file called commdlg.dll on 16-bit Windows, and comdlg32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] It is grouped under the *User Interface* category of the API.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The Common Control Library provides access to advanced user interface controls, including things like status bars, progress bars, toolbars and tabs.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The library resides in a DLL file called commctrl.dll on 16-bit Windows, and comctl32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The Windows Shell component provides access to the operating system shell.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The component resides in shell.dll on 16-bit Windows, and shell32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The Shell Lightweight Utility Functions are in shlwapi.dll.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Network Services provide access to the various networking abilities of the operating system.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Its subcomponents include NetBIOS, Winsock, NetDDE, remote procedure call (RPC) and many more.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] This component resides in netapi32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The Internet Explorer (IE) web browser exposes APIs and as such could be considered part of the Windows API.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] IE has been included with the operating system since Windows 95 OSR2 and has provided web-related services to applications since Windows 98.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The Windows API is a C language-based API.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Functions and data structures are consumable via C syntax by including windows.h, but the API can be consumed via any programming language that can inter-operate with the API data structures and calling conventions for function calls and callbacks.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Of note, the implementation of API functions has been developed in several languages other than C.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Despite the fact that C is not an object-oriented programming (OOP) language, the Windows API is somewhat object-oriented due to its use of handles.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Various other technologies from Microsoft and others make this object-oriented aspect more apparent by using an OOP language such as C++ — see Microsoft Foundation Class Library (MFC), Visual Component Library (VCL), GDI+.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Of note, Windows 8 provides the Windows API and the WinRT API, which is implemented in C++ and is object-oriented by design.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Windows.pas is a Delphi unit that exposes the features of Windows API – the Pascal equivalent of windows.h.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Many Microsoft technologies use the Windows API—as most software running on Windows does.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] As middle-ware between Windows API and an application, the following technologies provide some access to Windows API.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Some technologies are described as wrapping Windows API, but this is debatable since they don't provide or expose all of the capabilities of Windows API.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Although almost all Windows programs use the Windows API, on the Windows NT line of operating systems, programs that start early in the Windows startup process use the Native API instead.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The Windows API has always exposed a large part of the underlying structure of the Windows systems to programmers.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] This had the advantage of giving them much flexibility and power over their applications, but also creates great responsibility in how applications handle various low-level, sometimes tedious, operations that are associated with a graphical user interface.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] For example, a beginning C programmer will often write the simple "hello world" as their first assignment.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The working part of the program is only a single printf line within the main subroutine.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Charles Petzold, who wrote several books about programming for the Windows API, said: "The original hello world program in the Windows 1.0 SDK was a bit of a scandal.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] HELLO.C was about 150 lines long, and the HELLO.RC resource script had another 20 or so more lines.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] (...) Veteran programmers often curled up in horror or laughter when encountering the Windows hello-world program." Petzold explains that while it was the first Windows sample programs developers were introduced to, it was quite "fancy" and more complex than needed.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Tired of people ridiculing the length of the sample, he eventually reduced it to a simple MessageBox call.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Over the years, various changes and additions were made to Windows systems, and the Windows API changed and grew to reflect this.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The Windows API for Windows 1.0 supported fewer than 450 function calls, whereas modern versions of the Windows API support thousands.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] However, in general, the interface remained fairly consistent, and an old Windows 1.0 application will still look familiar to a programmer who is used to the modern Windows API.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Microsoft has made an effort to maintain backward compatibility.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] To achieve this, when developing new versions of Windows, Microsoft sometimes implemented workarounds to allow compatibility with third-party software that used the prior version in an undocumented or even inadvisable way.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Raymond Chen, a Microsoft developer who works on the Windows API, has said: "I could probably write for months solely about bad things apps do and what we had to do to get them to work again (often in spite of themselves).
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Which is why I get particularly furious when people accuse Microsoft of maliciously breaking applications during OS upgrades.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] One of the largest changes to the Windows API was the transition from Win16 (shipped in Windows 3.1 and older) to Win32 (Windows NT and Windows 95 and up).
[src:win32-api/windows-api] While Win32 was originally introduced with Windows NT 3.1 and Win32s allowed use of a Win32 subset before Windows 95, it was not until Windows 95 that widespread porting of applications to Win32 began.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] To ease the transition, in Windows 95, for developers outside and inside Microsoft, a complex scheme of API thunks was used that could allow 32-bit code to call into 16-bit code (for most of Win16 APIs) and vice versa.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] *Flat thunks* allowed 32-bit code to call into 16-bit libraries, and the scheme was used extensively inside Windows 95's libraries to avoid porting the whole OS to Win32 in one batch.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] In Windows NT, the OS was pure 32-bit, except parts for compatibility with 16-bit applications, and only generic thunks were available to thunk from Win16 to Win32, as for Windows 95.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The Platform SDK shipped with a compiler that could produce the code needed for these thunks.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Versions of 64-bit Windows are also able to run 32-bit applications via WoW64.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The SysWOW64 folder located in the Windows folder on the OS drive contains several tools to support 32-bit applications.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Each version of Microsoft Windows contains a version of Windows API, and almost every new version of Microsoft Windows has introduced additions and changes to the Windows API.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The name, Windows API, refers to essentially the same capability in each version of Windows, but there is another name for this capability that is based on major architectural aspects of the Windows version that contains it.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] When there was only one version, it was simply called Windows API.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Then, when the first major update was made, Microsoft gave it the name Win32 and gave the first version the name Win16.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The term Windows API refers to both versions and all subsequently developed major versions.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The Wine project provides a Win32 API compatibility layer for Unix-like platforms, between Linux kernel API and programs written for the Windows API.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] ReactOS goes a step further and aims to implement the full Windows operating system, working closely with the Wine project to promote code re-use and compatibility.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] DosWin32 and HX DOS Extender are other projects which emulate the Windows API to allow executing simple Windows programs from a DOS command line.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Odin is a project to emulate Win32 on OS/2, superseding the original Win-OS/2 emulation which was based on Microsoft code.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Other minor implementations include the MEWEL and Zinc libraries which were intended to implement a subset of the Win16 API on DOS (see List of platform-independent GUI libraries).
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Windows Interface Source Environment (WISE) was a licensing program from Microsoft which allowed developers to recompile and run Windows-based applications on Unix and Macintosh platforms.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] WISE SDKs were based on an emulator of the Windows API that could run on those platforms.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] To develop software that uses the Windows API, a compiler must be able to use the Microsoft-specific DLLs listed above (COM-objects are outside Win32 and assume a certain vtable layout).
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The compiler must either handle the header files that expose the interior API function names, or supply such files.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] For the language C++, Zortech (later Symantec, then Digital Mars), Watcom and Borland have all produced well-known commercial compilers that have been used often with Win16, Win32s, and Win32.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Some of them supplied *memory extenders*, allowing Win32 programs to run on Win16 with Microsoft's redistributable Win32s DLL.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The Zortech compiler was probably one of the first stable and usable C++ compilers for Windows programming, before Microsoft had a C++ compiler.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] For certain classes of applications, the compiler system should also be able to handle interface description language (IDL) files.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Collectively, these prerequisites (compilers, tools, libraries, and headers) are known as the *Microsoft Platform SDK*.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] As of 2016, the MinGW and Cygwin projects also provide such an environment based on the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), using a stand-alone header file set, to make linking against the Win32-specific DLLs simple.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] LCC-Win32 is a C compiler maintained by Jacob Navia, freeware for non-commercial use.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Pelles C is a freeware C compiler maintained by Pelle Orinius.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Free Pascal is a free software Object Pascal compiler that supports the Windows API.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The MASM32 package is a mature project providing support for the Windows API under Microsoft Macro Assembler (MASM) by using custom made or converted headers and libraries from the Platform SDK.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Flat assembler FASM allows building Windows programs without using an external linker, even when running on Linux.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Windows specific compiler support is also needed for Structured Exception Handling (SEH).
[src:win32-api/windows-api] This system serves two purposes: it provides a substrate on which language-specific exception handling can be implemented, and it is how the kernel notifies applications of exceptional conditions such as dereferencing an invalid pointer or stack overflow.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] The Microsoft/Borland C++ compilers had the ability to use this system as soon as it was introduced in Windows 95 and NT, however the actual implementation was undocumented and had to be reverse engineered for the Wine project and free compilers.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] SEH is based on pushing exception handler frames onto the stack, then adding them to a linked list stored in thread-local storage (the first field of the thread environment block).
[src:win32-api/windows-api] When an exception is thrown, the kernel and base libraries unwind the stack running handlers and filters as they are encountered.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Eventually, every exception unhandled by the application will be dealt with by the default backstop handler, which pops up the Windows common crash dialog.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Microsoft has plans to update the Windows API for modern C++ usage with their `win32metadata` project.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Currently, there is C++/WinRT and "Windows Implementation Library" (WIL) for doing this in modern C++.
[src:win32-api/windows-api] Microsoft has also created bindings for other languages, including C# and Rust for calling the Win32 API.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Originally developed by Microsoft, WPF was initially released as part of .NET Framework 3.0 in 2006.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] In 2018, Microsoft released WPF as open source under the MIT License.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF's design and its layout language XAML have been adopted by multiple other UI frameworks, such as UWP, .NET MAUI, and Avalonia.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF employs XAML, an XML-based language, to define and link various interface elements, and uses C# to define program behavior.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF applications are deployed as standalone desktop programs.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF supports a number of common user interface elements, such as 2D/3D rendering, fixed and adaptive documents, typography, vector graphics, runtime animation, and pre-rendered media.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] These elements can then be linked and manipulated based on various events, user interactions, and data bindings.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF was developed under the codename "Avalon", as part of the WinFX programming model for Windows "Longhorn".
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] In August 2004, Microsoft announced that components of WinFX would be backported to Windows XP and Windows Server 2003.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] It would later be released as part of .NET Framework 3.0, a free download for these operating systems.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF runtime libraries are included with all versions of Microsoft Windows since Windows Vista and Windows Server 2008.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] At the Microsoft Connect event on December 4, 2018, Microsoft announced releasing WPF as open source project on GitHub.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Windows Presentation Foundation has become available for projects targeting the .NET software framework, however, the system is not cross-platform and is still available only on Windows.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] In WPF, screens and other UI elements are defined using a pair of files: a XAML file and an associated C# file with the extension `.xaml.cs`, often referred to as a "code-behind".
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] The XAML file declaratively defines the layout, contents and other properties of the UI element, while the C# file allows exposure of code entry points for interactivity.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] In the above example, a UI element called `MainWindow` is declared as a subclass of the built-in `Window` class.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] The XAML file defines the layout, which in this example is a vertical collection of controls - a textblock outlining instructions to the user, a textbox for the user to type their name, a button to submit, and a results text block.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] When the button is clicked, the method `SubmitButton_Click` is called, which is defined in the `.xaml.cs` file.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] This function updates the final textblock to contain a message greeting the user, addressing them by their submitted name.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF supports most modern media types, including vector and raster images, audio, video, and can support both 2D and 3D rendering.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] It also supports implementing graphical effects on visual elements, such as HLSL pixel shaders and built-in effects such as blurs and drop shadows.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF mainly relies on vector graphics, which allows most controls and elements to be scaled without loss in quality or pixelization.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF employs data binding, a technique of propagating changes between user interface elements and the object model of the program.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] This would make the textblock display the value of the `Username` property.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] The direction data binding happens is configurable - it can be defined to go UI-to-source (eg. text entered into a textbox being propagated to a bound string property in code), or source-to-UI (eg. a visual clock being updated to display the current time stored in code), or bi-directional.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Data binding doesn't have any restrictions on types, and it is possible to bind structs, classes, or collections.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Converters can be used to transpose the values and types being used during binding - for example, binding a textbox to a DateTime property, but using a converter to display the time as a formatted localised date string.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Most properties on built-in controls can be databound, and custom-made controls can create bindable properties by defining Dependency Properties.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] MVVM, the architectural pattern encouraged by Microsoft for WPF developers, relies heavily on data binding.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Using templates and styles, developers can define the visuals and structure of UI elements.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] A style is a combination of property settings that can be applied to a UI element with a single property attribute.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] For example, a "blue radio button" style could be created and then be reused on any number of radio button controls throughout the program.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Styles can alter collections of properties of controls, but are not intended for significant structural changes.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Templates are a mechanism for defining alternative UI for portions of a WPF application.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] There are several template types available in WPF for different scenarios, but they all have the general purpose of defining the contents, layout and structure of a UI element.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] In WPF, many visual properties can be animated.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] This is exposed through dependency properties, which is the same underlying system that data binding relies on.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF animations are time-based, as opposed to frame-based.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Animation classes are based on the .NET type of property to be animated.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] For instance, changing the color of an element is done with the ColorAnimation class and animating the width of an element (which is typed as a double) is done with the DoubleAnimation class.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Animations can be grouped into Storyboards, which are the primary way to start, stop, pause and otherwise manipulate animations.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF natively supports paginated documents.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] It provides the `DocumentViewer` class, which is for reading fixed layout documents.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] The `FlowDocumentReader` class offers different view modes such as per-page or scrollable and also reflows text if the viewing area is resized.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] It supports both the Open XML Paper Specification and Open Packaging Conventions.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF includes a number of text rendering features, including OpenType, TrueType, and OpenType CFF (Compact Font Format) fonts.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] This means that WPF can support a wide number of text features, including ligatures, old-style numerals, swash variants, fraction, superscript and subscript, small caps, ruby characters, glyph substitution, multiple baselines, and kerning.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF handles texts in Unicode, and handles texts independent of global settings, such as system locale.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] In addition, fallback mechanisms are provided to allow writing direction (horizontal versus vertical) handled independent of font name; building international fonts from composite fonts, using a group of single-language fonts; composite fonts embedding.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Font linking and font fallback information is stored in a portable XML file, using composite font technology.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] The XML file has extension *.CompositeFont*.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] The WPF text engine also supports built-in spell checking.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] It also supports such features as automatic line spacing, enhanced international text, language-guided line breaking, hyphenation, and justification, bitmap effects, transforms, and text effects such as shadows, blur, glow, rotation etc.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Animated text is also supported; this refers to animated glyphs, as well as real-time changes in position, size, color, and opacity of the text.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF text rendering takes advantage of advances in ClearType technology, such as sub-pixel positioning, natural advance widths, Y-direction anti-aliasing, hardware-accelerated text rendering, as well as aggressive caching of pre-rendered text in video memory.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] ClearType cannot be turned off in older WPF 3.x applications.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Windows Forms features are possible through the use of the `ElementHost` and `WindowsFormsHost` classes.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF programs, via the P/Invoke feature of the CLR, can access native functionality such calling functions from Windows libraries.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] This allows the ability to communicate and operate other parts of the operating system, including unmanaged libraries.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF supports Windows Ink for pen-based input, and multi-touch input on Windows 7 and above.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] It also supports Microsoft UI Automation to allow developers to create accessible interfaces, and to expose the UI to automated test frameworks.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Following the success of markup languages for web development, WPF introduced eXtensible Application Markup Language (XAML; /ˈzæməl/), which is based on XML.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] XAML is designed as a more efficient method of developing application user interfaces.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] XAML is a declarative language, meaning the developer (or designer) describes the behavior and integration of components without the use of procedural programming.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Although it is rare that an entire application will be built completely in XAML, the introduction of XAML allows application designers to more effectively contribute to the application development cycle.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Using XAML to develop user interfaces also allows for separation of model and view, which is considered a good architectural principle.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] In XAML, elements and attributes map to classes and properties in the underlying APIs.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] As in web development, both layouts and specific themes are well suited to markup, but XAML is not required for either.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Indeed, all elements of WPF may be coded in a .NET language (C#, VB.NET).
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] The XAML code can ultimately be compiled into a managed assembly in the same way all .NET languages are.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF applications are Windows-only standalone desktop executables.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Historically, WPF supported compiling to XBAP, a file format intended to be shown in web browsers via a NPAPI plugin, but NPAPI and XBAP support was phased out of support by browsers, and XBAP compilation is now no longer included for WPF for .NET.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF is used to develop Visual Studio, Microsoft's flagship IDE, and was used for developing Microsoft Expression Blend.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF and its layout language, XAML, have influenced multiple other UI frameworks.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Silverlight (codenamed WPF/E - WPF Everywhere), released in 2007, is a deprecated cross-browser browser plugin.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Silverlight had a WPF-based implementation, including using XAML for layouting, that supported video, vector graphics, and animations.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Using add-ons, it was supported on Mozilla Firefox, Internet Explorer 6 and above, Google Chrome 42 and below and Apple Safari.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Microsoft encouraged developers to stop using Silverlight in 2015, and support was officially ended in 2021.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] After becoming open source in 2018, WPF inspired the development of Avalonia, an open-source .NET cross-platform XAML-based UI framework, distributed under the MIT License.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] While WPF only is intended for Windows, Avalonia also supports builds for web (via WebAssembly), MacOS, Android, iOS, and Linux.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Avalonia's name references WPF's in-development codename ("Avalon"), and markets itself as "a spiritual successor to WPF".
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Avalonia is currently used in tools made by Unity, GitHub and JetBrains.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] OpenSilver is framework designed to migrate WPF solutions to web using WebAssembly.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] OpenSilver 3.1, released in December 2024, included a XAML designer for use in Visual Studio Code.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Developers of WPF applications typically use Microsoft Visual Studio.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Visual Studio contains a combination XAML editor and WPF visual designer, beginning with Visual Studio 2008.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Prior to Visual Studio 2008, the WPF designer add-in, codenamed Cider, was the original release of a WYSIWYG editor for creating WPF windows, pages, and user controls.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] It was available for Visual Studio 2005 as a *Visual Studio 2005 extensions for .NET Framework 3.0 CTP* for the initial release of WPF.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Visual Studio is not strictly required to develop WPF projects, as solutions can be built in the command line using MSBuild.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Microsoft Blend is a designer-oriented tool that provides an artboard for the creation of WPF applications with 2D and 3D graphics, text and forms content.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] It generates XAML that may be exported into other tools and shares solution (sln files) and project formats (csproj, vbproj) with Microsoft Visual Studio.
[src:win32-api/windows-presentation-foundation] Microsoft Expression Design is a bitmap and 2D-vector graphics tool for exporting to XAML.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] WinRT is not a runtime in a traditional sense but rather a language-independent application binary interface based on COM to allow object-oriented APIs to be consumed from multiple languages, with services usually provided by a full-blown runtime, such as type activation.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] That is, WinRT is an "API delivery system".
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Apps using the Windows Runtime may run inside a sandboxed environment to allow greater security and stability and can natively support both x86 and ARM.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] WinRT components are designed with interoperability among multiple languages and APIs in mind, including native, managed and scripting languages.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Built-in APIs provided by Windows which use the WinRT ABI are commonly known as WinRT APIs; however, anyone can use the WinRT ABI for their own APIs.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] WinRT is implemented in the programming language C++ and is object-oriented by design.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Its underlying technology, the Windows API (Win32 API), is written mostly in the language C.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] It is an unmanaged application binary interface based on Component Object Model (COM) that allows interfacing from multiple languages, as does COM.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] However, the API definitions are stored in `.winmd` files, which are encoded in ECMA 335 metadata format, which .NET Framework also uses with a few modifications.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] For WinRT components implemented in native code, the metadata file only contains the definition of methods, classes, interfaces and enumerations and the implementation is provided in a separate DLL.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] This common metadata format makes it easier to consume WinRT APIs from .NET apps with simpler syntax than P/Invoke.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Windows provides a set of built-in APIs which are built on the WinRT ABI which provide everything from the XAML-based WinUI library and device access such as camera, microphone, etc.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The Component Extensions of C++/CX are recommended for use at the API-boundary only, not for other purposes.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Regular C++ (with COM-specific discipline) can also be used to program with WinRT components, with the help of the Windows Runtime C++ Template Library (WRL), which is similar in purpose to what Active Template Library provides for COM.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In 2019, Microsoft deprecated C++/CX in favor of the C++/WinRT header library.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Most WinRT applications run within a sandbox and need explicit user approval to access critical OS features and underlying hardware.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] By default, file access is restricted to several predetermined locations, such as the directories Documents or Pictures.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] WinRT applications are packaged in the .appx and later the .msix file format; based upon Open Packaging Conventions, it uses a ZIP format with added XML files.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] WinRT applications are distributed mostly through an application store named Microsoft Store, where Windows apps (termed *Windows Store apps*) can be purchased and downloaded by users.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Initially, WinRT apps could only be sideloaded from outside Windows Store on Windows 8 or RT systems that are part of a Windows domain, or equipped with a special activation key obtained from Microsoft.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] However these restrictions were lifted in the Windows 10 November Update, where users can freely sideload any app signed with a trusted certificate by enabling a setting.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In a major departure from Win32 and similarly to .NET Framework 4.5, most APIs which are expected to take significant time to complete are implemented as asynchronous.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] When calling a Windows Runtime asynchronous function, the task is started on another thread or process and the function returns immediately, freeing the app to perform other tasks while waiting for results.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The asynchronous model requires new programming language constructs.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Each language provides their own way to consume asynchronous APIs.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Parts of the built-in API needing asynchronous access include on-screen messages and dialogs, file access, Internet connectivity, sockets, streams, devices and services, and calendar, contacts and appointments.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The metadata describes the APIs written using the WinRT ABI.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] It defines a programming model that makes it possible to write object-oriented code that can be shared across programming languages, and enables services like reflective programming (reflection).
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Herb Sutter, C++ expert at Microsoft, explained during his session on C++ at the 2011 Build conference that the WinRT metadata is in the same format as CLI metadata.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Native code (i.e., processor-specific machine code) cannot contain metadata, so it is stored in a separate metadata file that can be reflected like ordinary CLI assemblies.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Since it is the same format as CLI metadata, WinRT APIs can be used from managed CLI languages as if it was just a .NET API.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] WinRT has a rich object-oriented class-based type system that is built on the metadata.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] It supports constructs with corresponding constructs in the .NET framework: classes, methods, properties, delegates, and events.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] One of the major additions to WinRT relative to COM is the cross-application binary interface (ABI), .NET-style generics.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Only interfaces and delegates can be generic, runtime classes and methods in them can't.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Generic interfaces are also known as parameterized interfaces.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In C++/CX, they are declared using the keyword `generic` with a syntax very similar to that of keyword `template`.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] WinRT classes (ref classes) can also be genericized using C++ templates, but only template instantiations can be exported to .winmd metadata (with some name mangling), unlike WinRT generics which preserve their genericity in the metadata.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] WinRT also provides a set of interfaces for generic containers that parallel those in the C++ Standard Library, and languages provide some reciprocal (back-and-forth) conversion functions.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The consumption of WinRT collections in .NET languages (e.g., C# and VB) and in JavaScript is more transparent than in C++, with automated mappings into their natural equivalents occurring behind the scenes.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] When authoring a WinRT component in a managed language, some extra, COM-style rules must be followed, e.g. .NET framework collection types cannot be declared as return types, but only the WinRT interfaces that they implement can be used at the component boundary.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Classes that are compiled to target the WinRT are called *WinRT components*.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] They are classes that can be written in any supported language and for any supported platform.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] This metadata makes it possible to interface with the component from any other WinRT language.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The runtime requires WinRT components that are built with .NET Framework to use the defined interface types or .NET type interfaces, which automatically map to the first named.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Inheritance is as yet not supported in managed WinRT components, except for XAML classes.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Programs and libraries targeted for the WinRT runtime can be created and consumed from several platforms and programming languages.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Notably C/C++ (either with language extensions offering first-class support for WinRT concepts, or with a lower-level template library allowing to write code in standard C++), .NET (C# and Visual Basic (.NET) (VB.NET)) and JavaScript.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Standard C++ is a *first-class citizen* of the WinRT platform.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] As of Windows 10, version 1803, the Windows SDK contains C++/WinRT.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] C++/WinRT is an entirely standard modern C++17 language projection for Windows Runtime (WinRT) APIs, implemented as a header-file-based library, and designed to provide first-class access to the modern Windows API.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] With C++/WinRT, Windows Runtime APIs can be authored and consumed using any standards-compliant C++17 compiler.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] WinRT is a native platform and supports any native (and standard) C++ code, so that a C++ developer can reuse existing native C/C++ libraries.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] With C++/WinRT, there are no language extensions.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] There are two other legacy options for using WinRT from C++: Windows Runtime C++ Template Library (WRL), an ATL-style template library (similar to Windows Template Library or WTL), and C++/CX (C++ with Component Extensions) which resembles C++/CLI.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Because of the internal consumption requirements at Microsoft, WRL is exception-free, meaning its return-value discipline is HRESULT-based just like that of COM.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] C++/CX on the other hand wraps-up calls to WinRT with code that does error checking and throws exceptions as appropriate.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] C++/CX has several extensions that enable integration with the platform and its type system.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The syntax resembles the one of C++/CLI although it produces native (although not standard) code and metadata that integrates with the runtime.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] For example, WinRT objects may be allocated with `ref new`, which is the counterpart of `gcnew` from C++/CLI.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The hat operator `^` retains its meaning, however in the case where both the caller and callee are written in C++ and living in the same process, a hat reference is simply a pointer to a vptr to a virtual method table (vtable, VMT).
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Along with C++/CX, relative to traditional C++ COM programming, are partial classes, again inspired by .NET.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] These allow instance WinRT XAML code to be translated into C++ code by tools, and then combined with human-written code to produce the complete class while allowing clean separation of the machine-generated and human-edited parts of a class implementation into different files.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The .NET Framework and the Common Language Runtime (CLR) are integrated into the WinRT as a subplatform.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] It has influenced and set the standards for the ecosystem through the metadata format and libraries.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The CLR provides services like JIT-compilation code and garbage collection.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] WinRT applications using .NET languages use the XAML-based WinUI, and are primarily written in C#, VB.NET, and for the first time for XAML, with native code using C++/CX.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Although not yet officially supported, programs can also be written in other .NET languages.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] With .NET 5, Microsoft removed the built-in WinRT support and instead created CsWinRT, a tool that generates interop code for accessing Windows Runtime APIs similar to how C++/WinRT works.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Classes defined in WinRT components that are built in managed .NET languages must be declared as `sealed`, so they cannot be derived from.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] However, non-sealed WinRT classes defined elsewhere can be inherited from in .NET, their virtual methods overridden, and so on; but the inherited managed class must still be sealed.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Members that interface with another language must have a signature with WinRT types or a managed type that is convertible to these.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] WinRT applications can also be coded using HTML with JavaScript in code-behind, which are run using the Trident rendering engine and Chakra JavaScript engine, both of which are also used by Internet Explorer.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] When coding a WinRT app in JavaScript, its features are adapted to follow JavaScript naming conventions, and namespaces are also mapped to JavaScript objects.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Microsoft is in the process of projecting WinRT APIs to languages other than C++.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] One example is Rust/WinRT, an interface for programs written in Rust to consume and author WinRT APIs.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Rust/WinRT is part of Windows App SDK (formerly Project Reunion), a Microsoft effort to reconcile traditional Windows desktop and the UWP app model.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] With the introduction of the Universal Windows Platform (UWP), the platform has received many API bridges that allow programs originally developed for other platforms to be ported easily while taking advantage of UWP features.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Microsoft has provided bridges for Android (defunct since 2016), iOS (Cocoa Touch), Progressive Web Apps, Silverlight, as well as traditional Windows desktop apps (using MSIX packaging from the Windows App SDK).
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] WinRT comes with an application programming interface (API) in the form of a class library that exposes the features of Windows 8 for the developer, like its immersive interface API.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] It is accessible and consumable from any supported language.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The Windows Runtime classes is a set SDKs that provide access to all functionality from the XAML parser to the camera function.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The SDKs are implemented as native C/C++ libraries (unmanaged).
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The naming conventions for the components (classes and other members) in the API are heavily influenced by the .NET naming conventions which uses camel case (specifically PascalCase).
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Microsoft recommends users to follow these rules in case where no others are given.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] These conventions are projected differently in some languages, like JavaScript, which converts it to its conventions and the other way around.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] This is to give a native and consistent experience regardless of the programming language.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Since Windows Runtime is projected to various languages, some restrictions on fundamental data types exist so as to host all such languages.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Programmers must be careful with the behavior of those types when used with public access (for method parameters, method return values, properties, etc.).
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In .NET languages and C++, a rich set of data types exists, representing various numerals.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] can only represent up to 53 bits of precision.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In WinRT, the only lacking numeral data type is 8-bit signed integer relative to .NET and C++.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] JavaScript developers must be careful when dealing with big numbers while coding for WinRT.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Strings are immutable in .NET and JavaScript, but mutable in C++.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In .NET and C++, structs are value types, and such a struct can contain any type in it.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] JavaScript does not directly support structs.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In WinRT, use of structs is allowed only for containing types that have value semantics, including numerals, strings, and other structs.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Pointers or interface references are disallowed.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In .NET, objects are passed by reference, whereas numerals and structs are passed by value.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In C++, all types can be passed by reference or value.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In WinRT, interfaces are passed by reference; all other types can be passed either by value or by reference.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In .NET, C++, and JavaScript arrays are reference types.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In WinRT, arrays are value types and quite restricted.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] property is used to subscribe to events.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In WinRT, all languages can use their own way to subscribe to events.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Some .NET collections map directly to WinRT collections.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] type resembles arrays and the array syntax is used to consume them.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] type is a key/value pair collection, and is projected as Dictionary in .NET languages.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] .NET and C++ also support overloading on type.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] In WinRT, only parameter number is used for overloading.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] All WinRT methods are designed such that any method taking longer than 50 milliseconds is an async method.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] For the full runtime library, all methods that have a chance to last longer than 50 ms are implemented as asynchronous methods only.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Windows Phone 8.1 uses a version of the Windows Runtime named the *Windows Phone Runtime*.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] It enables developing applications in C# and VB.NET, and Windows Runtime components in C++/CX.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Although WP8 brought limited support, the platform did eventually converge with Windows 8.1 in Windows Phone 8.1.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Windows Phone 8 has limited support for developing and consuming Windows Runtime components through *Windows Phone Runtime*.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Many of the Windows Runtime APIs in Windows 8 that handle core operating system functions have been ported to Windows Phone 8.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Support for developing native games using C++/CX and DirectX has been added, by request from the game development industry.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] However, the Windows Phone XAML Framework is still based on the same Microsoft Silverlight framework, as in Windows Phone 7, for backward compatibility.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Thus, as of 2016, XAML development is impossible in C++/CX.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Development using either HTML5 or WinJS is unsupported on Windows Phone 8.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Windows Runtime support on Windows Phone 8.1 converges with Windows 8.1.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The release brings a full Windows Runtime API to the platform, including support for WinRT XAML, and language bindings for C++/CX, and HTML5-JavaScript.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] There is also a project type called *Universal apps* to enable apps to share code across 8.1 versions of Windows Phone and Windows.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] The Windows Phone 8 Silverlight Framework has been updated.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] It can exploit some of the new features in the Windows Runtime.
[src:win32-api/windows-runtime] Windows Phone Runtime uses the AppX package format from Windows 8, after formerly using Silverlight XAP.
